<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,259,1905]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1447,1473]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName authority="(Sanskrit)" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Sanskrit" box="[582,666,1447,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="krishna">
<emphasis box="[582,666,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">krishna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (Sanskrit) means black, referring to the black coloration of the species in both the sexes; epithet to be treated as noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="362" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,259,1905]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1519,1545]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Biology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth" authorityYear="2021" box="[302,424,1519,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="krishna">
<emphasis box="[302,424,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">M. krishna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
breeds on 
<taxonomicName box="[547,719,1519,1545]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="catechu">
<emphasis box="[547,719,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Acacia catechu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) (
<taxonomicName box="[784,895,1519,1546]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
). Its populations start building up with the onset of southwest monsoon in May and continue to breed till the end of August when the population disappears again to reappear in the next May. Eggs are probably laid in the tender shoots. Nymphs are dark brown, smooth rather depressed and along with adults feed on shoots (
<figureCitation box="[688,767,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 12" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1929,1953]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,309,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-75@17.[151,1436,309,1906]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 12 A–C. Macropsis krishna sp. nov., adults on the plant Acacia catechu attended by the ant Camponotus sp. (A–B) and ecological habitat of M. krishna and M. nigrolineata in Hesaraghatta near Bengaluru (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4427951" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4427951/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
A–B) They are actively attended by the ant 
<taxonomicName box="[1256,1398,1628,1654]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1256,1398,1628,1654]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Camponotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName box="[159,318,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[328,461,1663,1690]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Formicidae</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth" authorityYear="2021" box="[480,602,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="krishna">
<emphasis box="[480,602,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">M. krishna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName box="[812,987,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrolineata">
<emphasis box="[812,987,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">M. nigrolineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and both the populations may be found on the same plant and attended by the same species of the ant (
<figureCitation box="[872,984,1699,1726]" captionStart="FIGURES 11" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,220,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-26@16.[151,1436,181,1843]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 11 A–G. Macropsis nigrolineata Viraktamath.A–E, variation in colour; F–G, adults and nymphs attended by the ant Camponotus sp. (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) on the plant Acacia catechu, in Hesaraghatta near Bengaluru." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4427949" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4427949/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Figs 11 F</figureCitation>
). The plant 
<taxonomicName box="[1121,1241,1699,1725]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="catechu">
<emphasis box="[1121,1241,1699,1725]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">A. catechu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grows in the dry deciduous forests in and around Bengaluru (
<figureCitation box="[646,749,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 12" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1929,1953]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,309,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-75@17.[151,1436,309,1906]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 12 A–C. Macropsis krishna sp. nov., adults on the plant Acacia catechu attended by the ant Camponotus sp. (A–B) and ecological habitat of M. krishna and M. nigrolineata in Hesaraghatta near Bengaluru (C)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4427951" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4427951/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Fig. 12C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="362" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,259,1905]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1771,1797]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth, 2021" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Yeshwanth" authorityYear="2021" box="[322,444,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="krishna" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[322,444,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">M. krishna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[451,541,1771,1797]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[451,541,1771,1797]" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has the crown well above level of pronotum as in 
<taxonomicName box="[1107,1287,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karnatakana">
<emphasis box="[1107,1287,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">M. karnatakana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Viraktamath" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hamiltoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">M. hamiltoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from both of them in the black coloration and in the shape of the pygofer ventral process that does not reach dorsal margin and in having a rimmed gonopore laterally and basally. These characters also distinguish this species from all other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[566,683,1880,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[566,683,1880,1905]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="362">Macropsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the subcontinent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
